post_text:
The first week of school was a huge success for our MVP students. It was great to see so many of our students return to the classroom. 2 days of in-person instruction for each grouping mixed with remote learning using our hybrid schedule allowed for students to connect with teachers and other classmates during “real time “ instruction. A big thank you to all the parents, staff, custodial team and administration for all the preparation, cooperation, teamwork, and tremendous safety precautions to make our opening possible. 💚💛🐉
Today the teachers spent the afternoon participating in professional development workshops working on different remote learning strategies to help enhance their lessons and look at different strategies of blended learning 👩‍🏫👩🏻‍💻📓💻📗👨🏽‍💻👨‍🏫

post_text:
MVP welcomes Mr. Crosland to the administrative staff this year. Mr. Crosland held his first parent meeting workshop today called “ Welcome Back Families - " A NEW WAY OF LEARNING". In this workshop, Ms. Allocca spoke to parents about the blended learning of instruction and what a day of remote learning looks like from starting with a remote check-in and ending in connecting with teacher’s for additional support at the end of the school day.
Mr. Crosland discussed and provided parents with a check list to explore ways to help their child during this time of educational change.👩🏼‍💻👨🏻‍💻

post_text:
Welcome Back!!!

The Teachers and Administration of Middle Village Prep were so excited to welcome back their students for the first time since Remote Learning began in March.
It was great to see so many of our students return today to begin the 2020-2021 school year. We want to wish all our students good luck this year especially our new 6th grade students who are joining our MVP family. A big thank you to our parents and students for following all the procedures for social distancing and for making the 1st day back to school a great experience!
#MVP💚💛😷📓💻📚

We are happy to announce that Middle Village Prep Charter School has been notified that for a 2nd year in a row has been recognized as a Recognition School.

Recognition schools are the highest performing and rapidly improving schools across the state. Recognition Schools demonstrate the relentless commitment of teachers, administrators, staff and parents, without whom this growth would not have been possible.

New York State Interim Education Commissioner Shannon Tahoe identified 582 high achieving schools, including 37 charter schools, from across New York State as Recognition Schools. We are very happy to see our school on this list as one of the top 13% in the state!

We are very proud of this accomplishment and proud of our MVP students and teachers for being so successful!

post_text: Our 7th Grade students took a virtual tour to explore the works of African American artist Romare Bearden as well as French painter Paul Cezanne. Once students scavenge through the artist's work, they read a biography and answer comprehension questions for a class assignment. Once this is done, they are free to choose any artist artwork they would like or to follow along with a video demonstration from Ms.veloz in order to recreate some of the most ground-breaking work the artists have done.

post_text:
MVP wants to wish good luck to our 8th grade students who will be notified today of their Public High School Acceptance!

Your high school offer letter will become available in MySchools and will also be mailed to your home address.

Your Offer Letter will include your high school offer and also include a SHSAT score if you took the SHSAT, and/or information about your LaGuardia High School audition if you auditioned.

Additionally, this letter will include a list of programs where you've been waitlisted. You’ll be automatically added to the waitlist of any program that you listed higher on your application than the program where you received an offer. For example, if you got an offer from your 5th choice, you would be on the waitlists of choices 1-4.

If you have any questions please make sure to reach out to our guidance department on Monday for further support

The deadline for its completion and submission is March 31st. The more parent participation that is received, the greater the opportunities that MVP administration and faculty members will have to address the needs of the students and the parents. This enables us to continue to provide high quality education and support services to your children.

You will have access to a computer so that you can complete the survey on line. In order to do this you must bring the envelope so that you can use the code given, to get access to the survey.

post_text:
On Wednesday, MVP students were selected to join a “one-of -a -kind event”- it is the first time that Madison Square Garden opened its doors to Broadway and along with 18,000 middle school and high school students - the 8th grade class and teachers were able to see the Broadway Show adaptation of Harper Lee's iconic book- “To Kill A Mockingbird”
Thousands of middle and high school students from all five boroughs were able to see the show for free, thanks to the chairman and CEO of Madison Square Garden.
Mayor Bill De Blasio and First Lady Chirlane McCray, as well as filmmaker Spike Lee, introduced the performance. The mayor has also declared February 26 “To Kill a Mockingbird Day.”

post_text: 7th Grade Students will be taking a trip to the Museum of Modern Art in order to help them make connections between the artwork that they learned in 6th, 7th and next year in 8th grade, and real life artmaking. This will allow students to see the original work behind many of their projects and experience modern art with their own eyes, through artists like Pablo Picasso, Claude Monet, Vincent Van Gogh, Frida Kahlo and Georgia O'keeffe. This trip is an opportunity for students to see how the arts can translate into future careers and studies and push the borders of their classroom views. Today was 7E’s turn, next week 7A,7B, 7C and 7D will be visiting MOMA.
